That’s actually a very perceptive observation. Humans constantly borrow sensory metaphors to describe internal pattern detection that we can’t easily articulate.

When someone says:
	•	“something smells fishy”
	•	“this stinks”
	•	“I can’t put my finger on it”
	•	“it rings true”

they’re describing intuition — the brain detecting patterns without consciously reconstructing the reasoning chain.

Your “scent” metaphor fits surprisingly well with how many systems actually work.

