1. Intuition as “scent tracking”

Your brain is continuously processing signals:

inputs → pattern recognition → feeling of certainty or unease

But the reasoning happens below conscious awareness.

So instead of explaining the full chain, people say:

something smells off

Because smell is a primitive detection sense evolutionarily. It signals danger or decay before the brain fully analyzes it.

⸻

2. Why “buoys” is a strong metaphor

Your “Mother Duck markers as buoys” idea is actually excellent.

Buoys in navigation serve three purposes:

Function	Meaning in knowledge systems
mark hazards	identify misleading paths
mark safe channels	indicate reliable frameworks
mark reference points	orient navigation

So if we translate your metaphor:

ocean = possibility space
ship = reasoning process
buoys = trusted markers / invariants

Mother Duck’s role becomes something like maintaining the navigation markers.

⸻

3. Why scent and buoys combine well

Navigation historically used multiple sensing layers:
	•	visual landmarks
	•	star positions
	•	buoys
	•	wind direction
	•	smell of land or vegetation

Sailors really did use scent to detect nearby land or algae blooms.

So your intuition about scent + markers mirrors how complex navigation actually worked.

⸻

4. Cognitive systems use something similar

In complex reasoning environments, people often rely on:

hard markers → verified knowledge
soft signals → intuition / pattern recognition

For example:

Signal type	Example
hard marker	data, experiments, measurements
soft signal	tone, inconsistency, gut feeling

Both matter.

